14/*
15Class twmxwStaticText is a specialization of wxStaticText that allows one to
16specify the font size in the constructor. Also, it provides a set of routines
17for setting the value from higher-level objects using a formatting string. For
18most POD types (floats, ints, unsigned, char, char*, etc.) use the regular
19formatting codes. For bools and all higher-level objects, e.g.,
20pointers-to-tmPart (which are referenced by their indices) use the formatting
21code %s.
22*/
23

30{

32 case 9:
33 SetFont(DEFAULT_FONT_9);
34 break;
35 case 10:
36 SetFont(DEFAULT_FONT_10);
37 break;
38 case 11:
39 SetFont(DEFAULT_FONT_11);
40 break;
41 case 12:
42 SetFont(DEFAULT_FONT_12);
43 break;
44 default:

51/*****
52Set the values from a C string. The format should contain %s.
53*****/
54void tmwxStaticText::SetLabelFormatted(const wxChar* format, const wxString& c)
55{
56 wxString text;
57 text.Printf(format, c.c_str());
58 SetLabel(text);
59}

62/*****
63Set the values from a bool. The format should contain %s (which will be
64replaced by "true" or "false", as appropriate).
65*****/
66void tmwxStaticText::SetLabelFormatted(const wxChar* format, bool b)
67{
68 wxString text;
69 if (b) text.Printf(format, wxT("true")L"true");
70 else text.Printf(format,wxT("false")L"false");
71 SetLabel(text);
72}

200/*****
201Set the value from a tmNodeOwner*. The format should contain %s.
202A tmNodeOwner can be a tmTree or a tmPoly
203*****/
204void tmwxStaticText::SetLabelFormatted(const wxChar* format,
205 const tmNodeOwner* p)
206{
207 wxString text;
208 const tmTree* theTree = dynamic_cast<const tmTree*>(p);
209 const tmPoly* thePoly = dynamic_cast<const tmPoly*>(p);
210 if (theTree) text.Printf(wxT("tree %s")L"tree %s", tmwxStr(theTree).c_str());
211 else if (thePoly) text.Printf(wxT("poly %s")L"poly %s", tmwxStr(thePoly).c_str());
212 else text.Printf(wxT("-")L"-");
213 SetLabelFormatted(format, text);
214}
215

315/*****

317*****/
318void tmwxStaticText::SetLabelFeasible(const tmCondition* c)
319{
320 if (c->IsFeasibleCondition())
321 SetLabel(wxT("condition currently feasible")L"condition currently feasible");
322 else
323 SetLabel(wxT("condition currently infeasible")L"condition currently infeasible");
324}

1///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
2// Name: wx/strvararg.h
3// Purpose: macros for implementing type-safe vararg passing of strings
4// Author: Vaclav Slavik
5// Created: 2007-02-19
6// Copyright: (c) 2007 REA Elektronik GmbH
7// Licence: wxWindows licence
8///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
9
10#ifndef _WX_STRVARARG_H_
11#define _WX_STRVARARG_H_
12
13#include "wx/platform.h"

15#include "wx/cpp.h"

18#include "wx/buffer.h"
19#include "wx/unichar.h"

21#if defined(HAVE_TYPE_TRAITS1)
22 #include <type_traits>
23#elif defined(HAVE_TR1_TYPE_TRAITS)
24 #ifdef __VISUALC__
25 #include <type_traits>

31class WXDLLIMPEXP_FWD_BASE wxCStrData;
32class WXDLLIMPEXP_FWD_BASE wxString;
33
34// There are a lot of structs with intentionally private ctors in this file,
35// suppress gcc warnings about this.
36wxGCC_WARNING_SUPPRESS(ctor-dtor-privacy)GCC diagnostic push GCC diagnostic ignored "-Wctor-dtor-privacy"
37
38// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
39// WX_DEFINE_VARARG_FUNC* macros
40// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
41
42// This macro is used to implement type-safe wrappers for variadic functions
43// that accept strings as arguments. This makes it possible to pass char*,
44// wchar_t* or even wxString (as opposed to having to use wxString::c_str())
45// to e.g. wxPrintf().
46//
47// This is done by defining a set of N template function taking 1..N arguments
48// (currently, N is set to 30 in this header). These functions are just thin
49// wrappers around another variadic function ('impl' or 'implUtf8' arguments,
50// see below) and the only thing the wrapper does is that it normalizes the
51// arguments passed in so that they are of the type expected by variadic
52// functions taking string arguments, i.e., char* or wchar_t*, depending on the
53// build:
54// * char* in the current locale's charset in ANSI build
55// * char* with UTF-8 encoding if wxUSE_UNICODE_UTF8 and the app is running
56// under an UTF-8 locale
57// * wchar_t* if wxUSE_UNICODE_WCHAR or if wxUSE_UNICODE_UTF8 and the current
58// locale is not UTF-8
59//
60// Note that wxFormatString *must* be used for the format parameter of these
61// functions, otherwise the implementation won't work correctly. Furthermore,
62// it must be passed by value, not reference, because it's modified by the
63// vararg templates internally.
64//
65// Parameters:
66// [ there are examples in square brackets showing values of the parameters
67// for the wxFprintf() wrapper for fprintf() function with the following
68// prototype:
69// int wxFprintf(FILE *stream, const wxString& format, ...); ]
70//
71// rettype Functions' return type [int]
72// name Name of the function [fprintf]
73// numfixed The number of leading "fixed" (i.e., not variadic)
74// arguments of the function (e.g. "stream" and "format"
75// arguments of fprintf()); their type is _not_ converted
76// using wxArgNormalizer<T>, unlike the rest of
77// the function's arguments [2]
78// fixed List of types of the leading "fixed" arguments, in
79// parentheses [(FILE*,const wxString&)]
80// impl Name of the variadic function that implements 'name' for
81// the native strings representation (wchar_t* if
82// wxUSE_UNICODE_WCHAR or wxUSE_UNICODE_UTF8 when running under
83// non-UTF8 locale, char* in ANSI build) [wxCrt_Fprintf]
84// implUtf8 Like 'impl', but for the UTF-8 char* version to be used
85// if wxUSE_UNICODE_UTF8 and running under UTF-8 locale
86// (ignored otherwise) [fprintf]
87//
88#define WX_DEFINE_VARARG_FUNC(rettype, name, numfixed, fixed, impl, implUtf8)inline rettype name(_WX_VARARG_FIXED_EXPAND_numfixed fixed) {
return impl(_WX_VARARG_JOIN_numfixed(_WX_VARARG_PASS_FIXED))
; } template<typename T1> rettype name(_WX_VARARG_FIXED_EXPAND_numfixed
fixed, T1 a1) { _WX_VARARG_FIXED_TYPEDEFS_numfixed fixed; const
wxFormatString *fmt = (_WX_VARARG_JOIN_numfixed(_WX_VARARG_FIND_FMT
)); return impl(_WX_VARARG_JOIN_numfixed(_WX_VARARG_PASS_FIXED
), wxArgNormalizerWchar<T1>(a1, fmt, 1).get()); } template
<typename T1, typename T2> rettype name(_WX_VARARG_FIXED_EXPAND_numfixed
fixed, T1 a1, T2 a2) { _WX_VARARG_FIXED_TYPEDEFS_numfixed fixed
; const wxFormatString *fmt = (_WX_VARARG_JOIN_numfixed(_WX_VARARG_FIND_FMT
)); return impl(_WX_VARARG_JOIN_numfixed(_WX_VARARG_PASS_FIXED
), wxArgNormalizerWchar<T1>(a1, fmt, 1).get(), wxArgNormalizerWchar
<T2>(a2, fmt, 2).get()); } template<typename T1, typename
T2, typename T3> rettype name(_WX_VARARG_FIXED_EXPAND_numfixed

125// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
126// wxFormatString
127// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
128
129// This class must be used for format string argument of the functions
130// defined using WX_DEFINE_VARARG_FUNC_* macros. It converts the string to
131// char* or wchar_t* for passing to implementation function efficiently (i.e.
132// without keeping the converted string in memory for longer than necessary,
133// like c_str()). It also converts format string to the correct form that
134// accounts for string changes done by wxArgNormalizer<>
135//
136// Note that this class can _only_ be used for function arguments!
137class WXDLLIMPEXP_BASE__attribute__ ((visibility("default"))) wxFormatString
138{
139public:
140#ifndef wxNO_IMPLICIT_WXSTRING_ENCODING
141 wxFormatString(const char *str)
142 : m_char(wxScopedCharBuffer::CreateNonOwned(str)), m_str(NULL__null), m_cstr(NULL__null) {}
143#endif
144 wxFormatString(const wchar_t *str)
145 : m_wchar(wxScopedWCharBuffer::CreateNonOwned(str)), m_str(NULL__null), m_cstr(NULL__null) {}
2
←
Calling 'wxScopedCharTypeBuffer::CreateNonOwned'
→
14
←
Returning; memory was released
→
146 wxFormatString(const wxString& str)
147 : m_str(&str), m_cstr(NULL__null) {}
148 wxFormatString(const wxCStrData& str)
149 : m_str(NULL__null), m_cstr(&str) {}
150#ifndef wxNO_IMPLICIT_WXSTRING_ENCODING
151 wxFormatString(const wxScopedCharBuffer& str)
152 : m_char(str), m_str(NULL__null), m_cstr(NULL__null) {}
153#endif
154 wxFormatString(const wxScopedWCharBuffer& str)
155 : m_wchar(str), m_str(NULL__null), m_cstr(NULL__null) {}
156
157 // Possible argument types. These are or-combinable for wxASSERT_ARG_TYPE
158 // convenience. Some of the values are or-combined with another value, this
159 // expresses "supertypes" for use with wxASSERT_ARG_TYPE masks. For example,
160 // a char* string is also a pointer and an integer is also a char.
161 enum ArgumentType
162 {
163 Arg_Unused = 0, // not used at all; the value of 0 is chosen to
164 // conveniently pass wxASSERT_ARG_TYPE's check
165
166 Arg_Char = 0x0001, // character as char %c
167 Arg_Pointer = 0x0002, // %p
168 Arg_String = 0x0004 | Arg_Pointer, // any form of string (%s and %p too)
169
170 Arg_Int = 0x0008 | Arg_Char, // (ints can be used with %c)
171#if SIZEOF_INT4 == SIZEOF_LONG8
172 Arg_LongInt = Arg_Int,
173#else
174 Arg_LongInt = 0x0010,
175#endif
176#if defined(SIZEOF_LONG_LONG8) && SIZEOF_LONG_LONG8 == SIZEOF_LONG8
177 Arg_LongLongInt = Arg_LongInt,
178#elif defined(wxLongLong_tlong long)
179 Arg_LongLongInt = 0x0020,
180#endif
181
182 Arg_Double = 0x0040,
183 Arg_LongDouble = 0x0080,
184
185#if defined(wxSIZE_T_IS_UINT)
186 Arg_Size_t = Arg_Int,
187#elif defined(wxSIZE_T_IS_ULONG1)
188 Arg_Size_t = Arg_LongInt,
189#elif defined(SIZEOF_LONG_LONG8) && SIZEOF_SIZE_T8 == SIZEOF_LONG_LONG8
190 Arg_Size_t = Arg_LongLongInt,
191#else
192 Arg_Size_t = 0x0100,
193#endif
194
195 Arg_IntPtr = 0x0200, // %n -- store # of chars written
196 Arg_ShortIntPtr = 0x0400,
197 Arg_LongIntPtr = 0x0800,
198
199 Arg_Unknown = 0x8000 // unrecognized specifier (likely error)
200 };
201
202 // returns the type of format specifier for n-th variadic argument (this is
203 // not necessarily n-th format specifier if positional specifiers are used);
204 // called by wxArgNormalizer<> specializations to get information about
205 // n-th variadic argument desired representation
206 ArgumentType GetArgumentType(unsigned n) const;
207
208 // returns the value passed to ctor, only converted to wxString, similarly
209 // to other InputAsXXX() methods
210 wxString InputAsString() const;
211
212#if !wxUSE_UNICODE_WCHAR1 && !defined wxNO_IMPLICIT_WXSTRING_ENCODING
213 operator const char*() const
214 { return const_cast<wxFormatString*>(this)->AsChar(); }
215private:
216 // InputAsChar() returns the value passed to ctor, only converted
217 // to char, while AsChar() takes the string returned by InputAsChar()
218 // and does format string conversion on it as well (and similarly for
219 // ..AsWChar() below)
220 const char* InputAsChar();
221 const char* AsChar();
222 wxScopedCharBuffer m_convertedChar;
223#endif // !wxUSE_UNICODE_WCHAR && !defined wx_NO_IMPLICIT_WXSTRING_ENCODING
224
225#if wxUSE_UNICODE1 && !wxUSE_UTF8_LOCALE_ONLY0
226public:
227 operator const wchar_t*() const
228 { return const_cast<wxFormatString*>(this)->AsWChar(); }
229private:
230 const wchar_t* InputAsWChar();
231 const wchar_t* AsWChar();
232 wxScopedWCharBuffer m_convertedWChar;
233#endif // wxUSE_UNICODE && !wxUSE_UTF8_LOCALE_ONLY
234
235private:
236 wxScopedCharBuffer m_char;
237 wxScopedWCharBuffer m_wchar;
238
239 // NB: we can use a pointer here, because wxFormatString is only used
240 // as function argument, so it has shorter life than the string
241 // passed to the ctor
242 const wxString * const m_str;
243 const wxCStrData * const m_cstr;
244
245 wxDECLARE_NO_ASSIGN_CLASS(wxFormatString)private: wxFormatString& operator=(const wxFormatString&
) = delete;
246};
247
248// these two helper classes are used to find wxFormatString argument among fixed
249// arguments passed to a vararg template
250struct wxFormatStringArgument
251{
252 wxFormatStringArgument(const wxFormatString *s = NULL__null) : m_str(s) {}
253 const wxFormatString *m_str;
254
255 // overriding this operator allows us to reuse _WX_VARARG_JOIN macro
256 wxFormatStringArgument operator,(const wxFormatStringArgument& a) const
257 {
258 wxASSERT_MSG( m_str == NULL || a.m_str == NULL,do { if ( m_str == __null || a.m_str == __null ) { } else if (
wxTheAssertHandler && (wxOnAssert("/opt/homebrew/include/wx-3.2/wx/strvararg.h"
, 259, __FUNCTION__, "m_str == __null || a.m_str == __null", "can't have two format strings in vararg function"
), wxTrapInAssert) ) { wxTrapInAssert = false; wxTrap(); } } while
( (void)0, 0 )
259 "can't have two format strings in vararg function" )do { if ( m_str == __null || a.m_str == __null ) { } else if (
wxTheAssertHandler && (wxOnAssert("/opt/homebrew/include/wx-3.2/wx/strvararg.h"
, 259, __FUNCTION__, "m_str == __null || a.m_str == __null", "can't have two format strings in vararg function"
), wxTrapInAssert) ) { wxTrapInAssert = false; wxTrap(); } } while
( (void)0, 0 );
260 return wxFormatStringArgument(m_str ? m_str : a.m_str);

264};

266template<typename T>
267struct wxFormatStringArgumentFinder
268{
269 static wxFormatStringArgument find(T)
270 {
271 // by default, arguments are not format strings, so return "not found"
272 return wxFormatStringArgument();
273 }
274};
275
276template<>
277struct wxFormatStringArgumentFinder<const wxFormatString&>
278{
279 static wxFormatStringArgument find(const wxFormatString& arg)
280 { return wxFormatStringArgument(&arg); }
281};

285 : public wxFormatStringArgumentFinder<const wxFormatString&> {};

345#if defined(HAVE_TYPE_TRAITS1) || defined(HAVE_TR1_TYPE_TRAITS)
346
347// Note: this type is misnamed, so that the error message is easier to
348// understand (no error happens for enums, because the IsEnum=true case is
349// specialized).
350template<bool IsEnum>
351struct wxFormatStringSpecifierNonPodType {};
352
353template<>
354struct wxFormatStringSpecifierNonPodType<true>
355{
356 enum { value = wxFormatString::Arg_Int };
357};
358
359template<typename T>
360struct wxFormatStringSpecifier
361{
362#ifdef HAVE_TYPE_TRAITS1
363 typedef std::is_enum<T> is_enum;
364#elif defined HAVE_TR1_TYPE_TRAITS
365 typedef std::tr1::is_enum<T> is_enum;
366#endif
367 enum { value = wxFormatStringSpecifierNonPodType<is_enum::value>::value };
368};
369
370#else // !HAVE_(TR1_)TYPE_TRAITS
371
372template<typename T>
373struct wxFormatStringSpecifier
374{
375 // We can't detect enums without is_enum, so the only thing we can
376 // do is to accept unknown types. However, the only acceptable unknown
377 // types still are enums, which are promoted to ints, so return Arg_Int
378 // here. This will at least catch passing of non-POD types through ... at
379 // runtime.
380 //
381 // Furthermore, if the compiler doesn't have partial template
382 // specialization, we didn't cover pointers either.
383 enum { value = wxFormatString::Arg_Int };
384};
385
386#endif // HAVE_TR1_TYPE_TRAITS/!HAVE_TR1_TYPE_TRAITS
387
388
389template<typename T>
390struct wxFormatStringSpecifier<T*>
391{
392 enum { value = wxFormatString::Arg_Pointer };
393};
394
395template<typename T>
396struct wxFormatStringSpecifier<const T*>
397{
398 enum { value = wxFormatString::Arg_Pointer };
399};

402#define wxFORMAT_STRING_SPECIFIER(T, arg) \
403 template<> struct wxFormatStringSpecifier<T> \
404 { \
405 enum { value = arg }; \
406 };

410 { \

412 wxFormatStringSpecifier() wxMEMBER_DELETE= delete; \
413 };

460wxFORMAT_STRING_SPECIFIER(long int*, wxFormatString::Arg_LongIntPtr | wxFormatString::Arg_Pointer)
461
462#ifdef wxHAS_NULLPTR_T
463wxFORMAT_STRING_SPECIFIER(std::nullptr_t, wxFormatString::Arg_Pointer)
464#endif
465
466#undef wxFORMAT_STRING_SPECIFIER
467#undef wxDISABLED_FORMAT_STRING_SPECIFIER

469
470// Converts an argument passed to wxPrint etc. into standard form expected,
471// by wxXXX functions, e.g. all strings (wxString, char*, wchar_t*) are
472// converted into wchar_t* or char* depending on the build.
473template<typename T>
474struct wxArgNormalizer
475{
476 // Ctor. 'value' is the value passed as variadic argument, 'fmt' is pointer
477 // to printf-like format string or NULL if the variadic function doesn't
478 // use format string and 'index' is index of 'value' in variadic arguments
479 // list (starting at 1)
480 wxArgNormalizer(T value,
481 const wxFormatString *fmt, unsigned index)
482 : m_value(value)
483 {
484 wxASSERT_ARG_TYPE( fmt, index, wxFormatStringSpecifier<T>::value )do { if ( !fmt ) break; const int argtype = fmt->GetArgumentType
(index); do { if ( (argtype & (wxFormatStringSpecifier<
T>::value)) == argtype ) { } else if ( wxTheAssertHandler &&
(wxOnAssert("/opt/homebrew/include/wx-3.2/wx/strvararg.h", 484
, __FUNCTION__, "(argtype & (wxFormatStringSpecifier<T>::value)) == argtype"
, "format specifier doesn't match argument type"), wxTrapInAssert
) ) { wxTrapInAssert = false; wxTrap(); } } while ( (void)0, 0
); } while ( (void)0, 0 );
485 }
486
487 // Returns the value in a form that can be safely passed to real vararg
488 // functions. In case of strings, this is char* in ANSI build and wchar_t*
489 // in Unicode build.
490 T get() const { return m_value; }
491
492 T m_value;
493};
494
495// normalizer for passing arguments to functions working with wchar_t* (and
496// until ANSI build is removed, char* in ANSI build as well - FIXME-UTF8)
497// string representation
498#if !wxUSE_UTF8_LOCALE_ONLY0
499template<typename T>
500struct wxArgNormalizerWchar : public wxArgNormalizer<T>
501{
502 wxArgNormalizerWchar(T value,
503 const wxFormatString *fmt, unsigned index)
504 : wxArgNormalizer<T>(value, fmt, index) {}
505};
506#endif // !wxUSE_UTF8_LOCALE_ONLY
507
508// normalizer for passing arguments to functions working with UTF-8 encoded
509// char* strings
510#if wxUSE_UNICODE_UTF80
511 template<typename T>
512 struct wxArgNormalizerUtf8 : public wxArgNormalizer<T>
513 {
514 wxArgNormalizerUtf8(T value,
515 const wxFormatString *fmt, unsigned index)
516 : wxArgNormalizer<T>(value, fmt, index) {}
517 };
518
519 #define wxArgNormalizerNativewxArgNormalizerWchar wxArgNormalizerUtf8
520#else // wxUSE_UNICODE_WCHAR
521 #define wxArgNormalizerNativewxArgNormalizerWchar wxArgNormalizerWchar
522#endif // wxUSE_UNICODE_UTF8 // wxUSE_UNICODE_UTF8

529// base class for wxArgNormalizer<T> specializations that need to do conversion;
530// CharType is either wxStringCharType or wchar_t in UTF-8 build when wrapping
531// widechar CRT function
532template<typename CharType>
533struct wxArgNormalizerWithBuffer
534{
535 typedef wxScopedCharTypeBuffer<CharType> CharBuffer;
536
537 wxArgNormalizerWithBuffer() {}
538 wxArgNormalizerWithBuffer(const CharBuffer& buf,
539 const wxFormatString *fmt,
540 unsigned index)
541 : m_value(buf)
542 {
543 wxASSERT_ARG_TYPE( fmt, index, wxFormatString::Arg_String )do { if ( !fmt ) break; const int argtype = fmt->GetArgumentType
(index); do { if ( (argtype & (wxFormatString::Arg_String
)) == argtype ) { } else if ( wxTheAssertHandler && (
wxOnAssert("/opt/homebrew/include/wx-3.2/wx/strvararg.h", 543
, __FUNCTION__, "(argtype & (wxFormatString::Arg_String)) == argtype"
, "format specifier doesn't match argument type"), wxTrapInAssert
) ) { wxTrapInAssert = false; wxTrap(); } } while ( (void)0, 0
); } while ( (void)0, 0 );
544 }
545
546 const CharType *get() const { return m_value; }
547
548 CharBuffer m_value;
549};

727// this macro is used to implement specialization that are exactly same as
728// some other specialization, i.e. to "forward" the implementation (e.g. for
729// T=wxString and T=const wxString&). Note that the ctor takes BaseT argument,
730// not T!
731#if wxUSE_UNICODE_UTF80
732 #if wxUSE_UTF8_LOCALE_ONLY0
733 #define WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD(T, BaseT) \
734 _WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD_IMPL(wxArgNormalizerUtf8, T, BaseT)
735 #else // possibly non-UTF8 locales
736 #define WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD(T, BaseT) \
737 _WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD_IMPL(wxArgNormalizerWchar, T, BaseT); \
738 _WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD_IMPL(wxArgNormalizerUtf8, T, BaseT)
739 #endif
740#else // wxUSE_UNICODE_WCHAR
741 #define WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD(T, BaseT) \
742 _WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD_IMPL(wxArgNormalizerWchar, T, BaseT)
743#endif // wxUSE_UNICODE_UTF8/wxUSE_UNICODE_WCHAR
744
745#define _WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD_IMPL(Normalizer, T, BaseT) \
746 template<> \
747 struct Normalizer<T> : public Normalizer<BaseT> \
748 { \
749 Normalizer(BaseT value, \
750 const wxFormatString *fmt, unsigned index) \
751 : Normalizer<BaseT>(value, fmt, index) {} \
752 }
753
754// non-reference versions of specializations for string objects
755WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD(wxString, const wxString&);
756WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD(wxCStrData, const wxCStrData&);
757
758// versions for passing non-const pointers:
759#ifndef wxNO_IMPLICIT_WXSTRING_ENCODING
760WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD(char*, const char*);
761#endif
762WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD(wchar_t*, const wchar_t*);
763
764// versions for passing wx[W]CharBuffer:
765#ifndef wxNO_IMPLICIT_WXSTRING_ENCODING
766WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD(wxScopedCharBuffer, const char*);
767WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD(const wxScopedCharBuffer&, const char*);
768#endif
769WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD(wxScopedWCharBuffer, const wchar_t*);
770WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD(const wxScopedWCharBuffer&, const wchar_t*);
771#ifndef wxNO_IMPLICIT_WXSTRING_ENCODING
772WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD(wxCharBuffer, const char*);
773WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD(const wxCharBuffer&, const char*);
774#endif
775WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD(wxWCharBuffer, const wchar_t*);
776WX_ARG_NORMALIZER_FORWARD(const wxWCharBuffer&, const wchar_t*);

873// versions for wxUniChar, wxUniCharRef:
874// (this is same for UTF-8 and Wchar builds, we just convert to wchar_t)
875template<>
876struct wxArgNormalizer<const wxUniChar&> : public wxArgNormalizer<wchar_t>
877{
878 wxArgNormalizer(const wxUniChar& s,
879 const wxFormatString *fmt, unsigned index)
880 : wxArgNormalizer<wchar_t>(wx_truncate_cast(wchar_t, s.GetValue())static_cast<wchar_t>(s.GetValue()), fmt, index) {}
881};
882
883// for wchar_t, default handler does the right thing
884
885// char has to be treated differently in Unicode builds: a char argument may
886// be used either for a character value (which should be converted into
887// wxUniChar) or as an integer value (which should be left as-is). We take
888// advantage of the fact that both char and wchar_t are converted into int
889// in variadic arguments here.
890#if wxUSE_UNICODE1
891template<typename T>
892struct wxArgNormalizerNarrowChar
893{
894 wxArgNormalizerNarrowChar(T value,
895 const wxFormatString *fmt, unsigned index)
896 {
897 wxASSERT_ARG_TYPE( fmt, index,do { if ( !fmt ) break; const int argtype = fmt->GetArgumentType
(index); do { if ( (argtype & (wxFormatString::Arg_Char |
wxFormatString::Arg_Int)) == argtype ) { } else if ( wxTheAssertHandler
&& (wxOnAssert("/opt/homebrew/include/wx-3.2/wx/strvararg.h"
, 898, __FUNCTION__, "(argtype & (wxFormatString::Arg_Char | wxFormatString::Arg_Int)) == argtype"
, "format specifier doesn't match argument type"), wxTrapInAssert
) ) { wxTrapInAssert = false; wxTrap(); } } while ( (void)0, 0
); } while ( (void)0, 0 )
898 wxFormatString::Arg_Char | wxFormatString::Arg_Int )do { if ( !fmt ) break; const int argtype = fmt->GetArgumentType
(index); do { if ( (argtype & (wxFormatString::Arg_Char |
wxFormatString::Arg_Int)) == argtype ) { } else if ( wxTheAssertHandler
&& (wxOnAssert("/opt/homebrew/include/wx-3.2/wx/strvararg.h"
, 898, __FUNCTION__, "(argtype & (wxFormatString::Arg_Char | wxFormatString::Arg_Int)) == argtype"
, "format specifier doesn't match argument type"), wxTrapInAssert
) ) { wxTrapInAssert = false; wxTrap(); } } while ( (void)0, 0
); } while ( (void)0, 0 );
899
900 // FIXME-UTF8: which one is better default in absence of fmt string
901 // (i.e. when used like e.g. Foo("foo", "bar", 'c', NULL)?
902 if ( !fmt || fmt->GetArgumentType(index) == wxFormatString::Arg_Char )
903 m_value = wx_truncate_cast(T, wxUniChar(value).GetValue())static_cast<T>(wxUniChar(value).GetValue());
904 else
905 m_value = value;
906 }
907
908 int get() const { return m_value; }
909
910 T m_value;
911};
912
913template<>
914struct wxArgNormalizer<char> : public wxArgNormalizerNarrowChar<char>
915{
916 wxArgNormalizer(char value,
917 const wxFormatString *fmt, unsigned index)
918 : wxArgNormalizerNarrowChar<char>(value, fmt, index) {}
919};

936 : wxArgNormalizerNarrowChar<signed char>(value, fmt, index) {}
937};

939#endif // wxUSE_UNICODE

958// WX_VA_ARG_STRING
959// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
960
961// Replacement for va_arg() for use with strings in functions that accept
962// strings normalized by wxArgNormalizer<T>:
963
964struct WXDLLIMPEXP_BASE__attribute__ ((visibility("default"))) wxArgNormalizedString
965{
966 wxArgNormalizedString(const void* ptr) : m_ptr(ptr) {}
967
968 // returns true if non-NULL string was passed in
969 bool IsValid() const { return m_ptr != NULL__null; }
970 operator bool() const { return IsValid(); }
971
972 // extracts the string, returns empty string if NULL was passed in
973 wxString GetString() const;
974 operator wxString() const;
975
976private:
977 const void *m_ptr;
978};

980#define WX_VA_ARG_STRING(ap)wxArgNormalizedString(__builtin_va_arg(ap, const void*)) wxArgNormalizedString(va_arg(ap, const void*)__builtin_va_arg(ap, const void*))

982// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
983// implementation of the WX_DEFINE_VARARG_* macros
984// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
985
986// NB: The vararg emulation code is limited to 30 variadic and 4 fixed
987// arguments at the moment.
988// If you need more variadic arguments, you need to
989// 1) increase the value of _WX_VARARG_MAX_ARGS
990// 2) add _WX_VARARG_JOIN_* and _WX_VARARG_ITER_* up to the new
991// _WX_VARARG_MAX_ARGS value to the lists below

1074 t1 WXUNUSED(f1), t2 WXUNUSED(f2)
1075#define _WX_VARARG_FIXED_UNUSED_EXPAND_3(t1,t2,t3)t1 , t2 , t3 \
1076 t1 WXUNUSED(f1), t2 WXUNUSED(f2), t3 WXUNUSED(f3)

1078 t1 WXUNUSED(f1), t2 WXUNUSED(f2), t3 WXUNUSED(f3), t4 WXUNUSED(f4)

1089// This macro expands N-items tuple of fixed arguments types into part of
1090// function's declaration. For example,
1091// "_WX_VARARG_FIXED_EXPAND(3, (int, char*, int))" expands into
1092// "int f1, char* f2, int f3".
1093#define _WX_VARARG_FIXED_EXPAND(N, args)_WX_VARARG_FIXED_EXPAND_N args \
1094 _WX_VARARG_FIXED_EXPAND_IMPL(N, args)_WX_VARARG_FIXED_EXPAND_N args
1095#define _WX_VARARG_FIXED_EXPAND_IMPL(N, args)_WX_VARARG_FIXED_EXPAND_N args \
1096 _WX_VARARG_FIXED_EXPAND_##N args
1097
1098// Ditto for unused arguments
1099#define _WX_VARARG_FIXED_UNUSED_EXPAND(N, args)_WX_VARARG_FIXED_UNUSED_EXPAND_N args \
1100 _WX_VARARG_FIXED_UNUSED_EXPAND_IMPL(N, args)_WX_VARARG_FIXED_UNUSED_EXPAND_N args
1101#define _WX_VARARG_FIXED_UNUSED_EXPAND_IMPL(N, args)_WX_VARARG_FIXED_UNUSED_EXPAND_N args \
1102 _WX_VARARG_FIXED_UNUSED_EXPAND_##N args
1103
1104// Declarates typedefs for fixed arguments types; i-th fixed argument types
1105// will have TFi typedef.
1106#define _WX_VARARG_FIXED_TYPEDEFS(N, args)_WX_VARARG_FIXED_TYPEDEFS_N args \
1107 _WX_VARARG_FIXED_TYPEDEFS_IMPL(N, args)_WX_VARARG_FIXED_TYPEDEFS_N args
1108#define _WX_VARARG_FIXED_TYPEDEFS_IMPL(N, args)_WX_VARARG_FIXED_TYPEDEFS_N args \
1109 _WX_VARARG_FIXED_TYPEDEFS_##N args
1110
1111
1112// This macro calls another macro 'm' passed as second argument 'N' times,
1113// with its only argument set to 1..N, and concatenates the results using
1114// comma as separator.
1115//
1116// An example:
1117// #define foo(i) x##i
1118// // this expands to "x1,x2,x3,x4"
1119// _WX_VARARG_JOIN(4, foo)
1120//
1121//
1122// N must not be greater than _WX_VARARG_MAX_ARGS (=30).
1123#define _WX_VARARG_JOIN(N, m)_WX_VARARG_JOIN_N(m) _WX_VARARG_JOIN_IMPL(N, m)_WX_VARARG_JOIN_N(m)
1124#define _WX_VARARG_JOIN_IMPL(N, m)_WX_VARARG_JOIN_N(m) _WX_VARARG_JOIN_##N(m)
1125
1126
1127// This macro calls another macro 'm' passed as second argument 'N' times, with
1128// its first argument set to 1..N and the remaining arguments set to 'a', 'b',
1129// 'c', 'd', 'e' and 'f'. The results are separated with whitespace in the
1130// expansion.
1131//
1132// An example:
1133// // this macro expands to:
1134// // foo(1,a,b,c,d,e,f)
1135// // foo(2,a,b,c,d,e,f)
1136// // foo(3,a,b,c,d,e,f)
1137// _WX_VARARG_ITER(3, foo, a, b, c, d, e, f)
1138//
1139// N must not be greater than _WX_VARARG_MAX_ARGS (=30).
1140#define _WX_VARARG_ITER(N,m,a,b,c,d,e,f)_WX_VARARG_ITER_N(m,a,b,c,d,e,f) \
1141 _WX_VARARG_ITER_IMPL(N,m,a,b,c,d,e,f)_WX_VARARG_ITER_N(m,a,b,c,d,e,f)
1142#define _WX_VARARG_ITER_IMPL(N,m,a,b,c,d,e,f)_WX_VARARG_ITER_N(m,a,b,c,d,e,f) \
1143 _WX_VARARG_ITER_##N(m,a,b,c,d,e,f)
1144
1145// Generates code snippet for i-th "variadic" argument in vararg function's
1146// prototype:
1147#define _WX_VARARG_ARG(i)Ti ai T##i a##i
1148
1149// Like _WX_VARARG_ARG_UNUSED, but outputs argument's type with WXUNUSED:
1150#define _WX_VARARG_ARG_UNUSED(i)Ti T##i WXUNUSED(a##i)
1151
1152// Generates code snippet for i-th type in vararg function's template<...>:
1153#define _WX_VARARG_TEMPL(i)typename Ti typename T##i
1154
1155// Generates code snippet for passing i-th argument of vararg function
1156// wrapper to its implementation, normalizing it in the process:
1157#define _WX_VARARG_PASS_WCHAR(i)wxArgNormalizerWchar<Ti>(ai, fmt, i).get() \
1158 wxArgNormalizerWchar<T##i>(a##i, fmt, i).get()
1159#define _WX_VARARG_PASS_UTF8(i)wxArgNormalizerUtf8<Ti>(ai, fmt, i).get() \
1160 wxArgNormalizerUtf8<T##i>(a##i, fmt, i).get()
1161
1162
1163// And the same for fixed arguments, _not_ normalizing it:
1164#define _WX_VARARG_PASS_FIXED(i)fi f##i
1165
1166#define _WX_VARARG_FIND_FMT(i)(wxFormatStringArgumentFinder<TFi>::find(fi)) \
1167 (wxFormatStringArgumentFinder<TF##i>::find(f##i))
1168

34 Owned,
35 NonOwned

38 UntypedBufferData(void *str, size_t len, Kind kind = Owned)
39 : m_str(str), m_length(len), m_ref(1), m_owned(kind == Owned) {}

155 // For some reasong clang-tidy gives a warning about using freed memory
156 // here even when this is not at all the case, seemingly because it doesn't
157 // follow reference counting logic, i.e. it assumes that it's possible to
158 // delete the data even when it's still referenced.
159 //
160 // Suppress the warning as it's extremely annoying to get it for every use
161 // of wxCharBuffer.
162 //
163 // NOLINTNEXTLINE(clang-analyzer-cplusplus.NewDelete)
164 CharType *data() { return m_data->Get(); }
165 // NOLINTNEXTLINE(clang-analyzer-cplusplus.NewDelete)
166 const CharType *data() const { return m_data->Get(); }
167 operator const CharType *() const { return data(); }
168 CharType operator[](size_t n) const { return data()[n]; }
169
170 size_t length() const { return m_data->m_length; }

Taking false branch
→
205 return;
206 if ( --m_data->m_ref == 0 )
9
←
Assuming the condition is true
→
10
←
Taking true branch
→
21
←
Use of memory after it is freed
207 delete m_data;
11
←
Memory is released
→
208 m_data = GetNullData();
209 }
210
211 // sets this object to a be copy of 'other'; if 'src' is non-owned,
212 // a deep copy is made and 'this' will contain new instance of the data
213 void MakeOwnedCopyOf(const wxScopedCharTypeBuffer& src)
214 {
215 this->DecRef();
216
217 if ( src.m_data == this->GetNullData() )
218 {
219 this->m_data = this->GetNullData();
220 }
221 else if ( src.m_data->m_owned )
222 {
223 this->m_data = src.m_data;
224 this->IncRef();
225 }
226 else
227 {
228 // if the scoped buffer had non-owned data, we have to make
229 // a copy here, because src.m_data->m_str is valid only for as long
230 // as 'src' exists
231 this->m_data = new Data
232 (
233 StrCopy(src.data(), src.length()),
234 src.length()
235 );
236 }
237 }
238
239 static CharType *StrCopy(const CharType *src, size_t len)
240 {
241 CharType *dst = (CharType*)malloc(sizeof(CharType) * (len + 1));
242 if ( dst )
243 memcpy(dst, src, sizeof(CharType) * (len + 1));
244 return dst;
245 }
246
247protected:
248 Data *m_data;
249};
250
251typedef wxScopedCharTypeBuffer<char> wxScopedCharBuffer;
252typedef wxScopedCharTypeBuffer<wchar_t> wxScopedWCharBuffer;

255// this buffer class always stores data in "owned" (persistent) manner
256template <typename T>
257class wxCharTypeBuffer : public wxScopedCharTypeBuffer<T>
258{
259protected:
260 typedef typename wxScopedCharTypeBuffer<T>::Data Data;
261
262public:
263 typedef T CharType;
264
265 wxCharTypeBuffer(const CharType *str = NULL__null, size_t len = wxNO_LEN((size_t)-1))
266 {
267 if ( str )
268 {
269 if ( len == wxNO_LEN((size_t)-1) )
270 len = wxStrlen(str);
271 this->m_data = new Data(this->StrCopy(str, len), len);
272 }
273 else
274 {
275 this->m_data = this->GetNullData();
276 }
277 }
278
279 wxCharTypeBuffer(size_t len)
280 {
281 CharType* const str = (CharType *)malloc((len + 1)*sizeof(CharType));
282 if ( str )
283 {
284 str[len] = (CharType)0;
285
286 // There is a potential memory leak here if new throws because it
287 // fails to allocate Data, we ought to use new(nothrow) here, but
288 // this might fail to compile under some platforms so until this
289 // can be fully tested, just live with this (rather unlikely, as
290 // Data is a small object) potential leak.
291 this->m_data = new Data(str, len);
292 }
293 else
294 {
295 this->m_data = this->GetNullData();
296 }
297 }
298
299 wxCharTypeBuffer(const wxCharTypeBuffer& src)
300 : wxScopedCharTypeBuffer<T>(src) {}
301
302 wxCharTypeBuffer& operator=(const CharType *str)
303 {
304 this->DecRef();
305
306 if ( str )
307 this->m_data = new Data(wxStrdup(str), wxStrlen(str));
308 return *this;
309 }
310
311 wxCharTypeBuffer& operator=(const wxCharTypeBuffer& src)
312 {
313 wxScopedCharTypeBuffer<T>::operator=(src);
314 return *this;
315 }
316
317 wxCharTypeBuffer(const wxScopedCharTypeBuffer<T>& src)
318 {
319 this->MakeOwnedCopyOf(src);
320 }
321
322 wxCharTypeBuffer& operator=(const wxScopedCharTypeBuffer<T>& src)
323 {
324 MakeOwnedCopyOf(src);
325 return *this;
326 }
327
328 bool extend(size_t len)
329 {
330 wxASSERT_MSG( this->m_data->m_owned, "cannot extend non-owned buffer" )do { if ( this->m_data->m_owned ) { } else if ( wxTheAssertHandler
&& (wxOnAssert("/opt/homebrew/include/wx-3.2/wx/buffer.h"
, 330, __FUNCTION__, "this->m_data->m_owned", "cannot extend non-owned buffer"
), wxTrapInAssert) ) { wxTrapInAssert = false; wxTrap(); } } while
( (void)0, 0 );
331 wxASSERT_MSG( this->m_data->m_ref == 1, "can't extend shared buffer" )do { if ( this->m_data->m_ref == 1 ) { } else if ( wxTheAssertHandler
&& (wxOnAssert("/opt/homebrew/include/wx-3.2/wx/buffer.h"
, 331, __FUNCTION__, "this->m_data->m_ref == 1", "can't extend shared buffer"
), wxTrapInAssert) ) { wxTrapInAssert = false; wxTrap(); } } while
( (void)0, 0 );
332
333 CharType *str =
334 (CharType *)realloc(this->data(), (len + 1) * sizeof(CharType));
335 if ( !str )
336 return false;
337
338 // For consistency with the ctor taking just the length, NUL-terminate
339 // the buffer.
340 str[len] = (CharType)0;
341
342 if ( this->m_data == this->GetNullData() )
343 {
344 this->m_data = new Data(str, len);
345 }
346 else
347 {
348 this->m_data->Set(str, len);
349 this->m_data->m_owned = true;
350 }
351
352 return true;
353 }
354
355 void shrink(size_t len)
356 {
357 wxASSERT_MSG( this->m_data->m_owned, "cannot shrink non-owned buffer" )do { if ( this->m_data->m_owned ) { } else if ( wxTheAssertHandler
&& (wxOnAssert("/opt/homebrew/include/wx-3.2/wx/buffer.h"
, 357, __FUNCTION__, "this->m_data->m_owned", "cannot shrink non-owned buffer"
), wxTrapInAssert) ) { wxTrapInAssert = false; wxTrap(); } } while
( (void)0, 0 );
358 wxASSERT_MSG( this->m_data->m_ref == 1, "can't shrink shared buffer" )do { if ( this->m_data->m_ref == 1 ) { } else if ( wxTheAssertHandler
&& (wxOnAssert("/opt/homebrew/include/wx-3.2/wx/buffer.h"
, 358, __FUNCTION__, "this->m_data->m_ref == 1", "can't shrink shared buffer"
), wxTrapInAssert) ) { wxTrapInAssert = false; wxTrap(); } } while
( (void)0, 0 );
359
360 wxASSERT( len <= this->length() )do { if ( len <= this->length() ) { } else if ( wxTheAssertHandler
&& (wxOnAssert("/opt/homebrew/include/wx-3.2/wx/buffer.h"
, 360, __FUNCTION__, "len <= this->length()", (const char
*)__null), wxTrapInAssert) ) { wxTrapInAssert = false; wxTrap
(); } } while ( (void)0, 0 );
361
362 this->m_data->m_length = len;
363 this->data()[len] = 0;
364 }
365};

445// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
446// A class for holding growable data buffers (not necessarily strings)
447// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
448
449// This class manages the actual data buffer pointer and is ref-counted.
450class wxMemoryBufferData
451{
452public:
453 // the initial size and also the size added by ResizeIfNeeded()
454 enum { DefBufSize = 1024 };
455
456 friend class wxMemoryBuffer;
457
458 // everything is private as it can only be used by wxMemoryBuffer
459private:
460 wxMemoryBufferData(size_t size = wxMemoryBufferData::DefBufSize)
461 : m_data(size ? malloc(size) : NULL__null), m_size(size), m_len(0), m_ref(0)
462 {
463 }
464 ~wxMemoryBufferData() { free(m_data); }
465
466
467 void ResizeIfNeeded(size_t newSize)
468 {
469 if (newSize > m_size)
470 {
471 void* const data = realloc(m_data, newSize + wxMemoryBufferData::DefBufSize);
472 if ( !data )
473 {
474 // It's better to crash immediately dereferencing a null
475 // pointer in the function calling us than overflowing the
476 // buffer which couldn't be made big enough.
477 free(release());
478 return;
479 }
480
481 m_data = data;
482 m_size = newSize + wxMemoryBufferData::DefBufSize;
483 }
484 }
485
486 void IncRef() { m_ref += 1; }
487 void DecRef()
488 {
489 m_ref -= 1;
490 if (m_ref == 0) // are there no more references?
491 delete this;
492 }
493
494 void *release()
495 {
496 if ( m_data == NULL__null )
497 return NULL__null;
498
499 wxASSERT_MSG( m_ref == 1, "can't release shared buffer" )do { if ( m_ref == 1 ) { } else if ( wxTheAssertHandler &&
(wxOnAssert("/opt/homebrew/include/wx-3.2/wx/buffer.h", 499,
__FUNCTION__, "m_ref == 1", "can't release shared buffer"), wxTrapInAssert
) ) { wxTrapInAssert = false; wxTrap(); } } while ( (void)0, 0
);
500
501 void *p = m_data;
502 m_data = NULL__null;
503 m_len =
504 m_size = 0;
505
506 return p;
507 }
508
509
510 // the buffer containing the data
511 void *m_data;
512
513 // the size of the buffer
514 size_t m_size;
515
516 // the amount of data currently in the buffer
517 size_t m_len;
518
519 // the reference count
520 size_t m_ref;
521
522 wxDECLARE_NO_COPY_CLASS(wxMemoryBufferData)private: wxMemoryBufferData(const wxMemoryBufferData&) = delete
; wxMemoryBufferData& operator=(const wxMemoryBufferData&
) = delete;
523};
524
525
526class wxMemoryBuffer
527{
528public:
529 // ctor and dtor
530 wxMemoryBuffer(size_t size = wxMemoryBufferData::DefBufSize)
531 {
532 m_bufdata = new wxMemoryBufferData(size);
533 m_bufdata->IncRef();
534 }
535
536 ~wxMemoryBuffer() { m_bufdata->DecRef(); }
537
538
539 // copy and assignment
540 wxMemoryBuffer(const wxMemoryBuffer& src)
541 : m_bufdata(src.m_bufdata)
542 {
543 m_bufdata->IncRef();
544 }
545
546 wxMemoryBuffer& operator=(const wxMemoryBuffer& src)
547 {
548 if (&src != this)
549 {
550 m_bufdata->DecRef();
551 m_bufdata = src.m_bufdata;
552 m_bufdata->IncRef();
553 }
554 return *this;
555 }
556
557
558 // Accessors
559 void *GetData() const { return m_bufdata->m_data; }
560 size_t GetBufSize() const { return m_bufdata->m_size; }
561 size_t GetDataLen() const { return m_bufdata->m_len; }
562
563 bool IsEmpty() const { return GetDataLen() == 0; }
564
565 void SetBufSize(size_t size) { m_bufdata->ResizeIfNeeded(size); }
566 void SetDataLen(size_t len)
567 {
568 wxASSERT(len <= m_bufdata->m_size)do { if ( len <= m_bufdata->m_size ) { } else if ( wxTheAssertHandler
&& (wxOnAssert("/opt/homebrew/include/wx-3.2/wx/buffer.h"
, 568, __FUNCTION__, "len <= m_bufdata->m_size", (const
char*)__null), wxTrapInAssert) ) { wxTrapInAssert = false; wxTrap
(); } } while ( (void)0, 0 );
569 m_bufdata->m_len = len;
570 }
571
572 void Clear() { SetDataLen(0); }
573
574 // Ensure the buffer is big enough and return a pointer to it
575 void *GetWriteBuf(size_t sizeNeeded)
576 {
577 m_bufdata->ResizeIfNeeded(sizeNeeded);
578 return m_bufdata->m_data;
579 }
580
581 // Update the length after the write
582 void UngetWriteBuf(size_t sizeUsed) { SetDataLen(sizeUsed); }
583
584 // Like the above, but appends to the buffer
585 void *GetAppendBuf(size_t sizeNeeded)
586 {
587 m_bufdata->ResizeIfNeeded(m_bufdata->m_len + sizeNeeded);
588 return (char*)m_bufdata->m_data + m_bufdata->m_len;
589 }
590
591 // Update the length after the append
592 void UngetAppendBuf(size_t sizeUsed)
593 {
594 SetDataLen(m_bufdata->m_len + sizeUsed);
595 }
596
597 // Other ways to append to the buffer
598 void AppendByte(char data)
599 {
600 wxCHECK_RET( m_bufdata->m_data, wxT("invalid wxMemoryBuffer") )if ( m_bufdata->m_data ) {} else { do { if ( wxTheAssertHandler
&& (wxOnAssert("/opt/homebrew/include/wx-3.2/wx/buffer.h"
, 600, __FUNCTION__, "\"m_bufdata->m_data\"", L"invalid wxMemoryBuffer"
), wxTrapInAssert) ) { wxTrapInAssert = false; wxTrap(); } } while
( (void)0, 0 ); return; } struct wxDummyCheckStruct600;
601
602 m_bufdata->ResizeIfNeeded(m_bufdata->m_len + 1);
603 *(((char*)m_bufdata->m_data) + m_bufdata->m_len) = data;
604 m_bufdata->m_len += 1;
605 }
606
607 void AppendData(const void *data, size_t len)
608 {
609 memcpy(GetAppendBuf(len), data, len);
610 UngetAppendBuf(len);
611 }
612
613 operator const char *() const { return (const char*)GetData(); }
614
615 // gives up ownership of data, returns the pointer; after this call,
616 // data isn't freed by the buffer and its content is resent to empty
617 void *release()
618 {
619 return m_bufdata->release();
620 }
621
622private:
623 wxMemoryBufferData* m_bufdata;
624};
